{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_0169p5ShXrn8NrNKyVyKx2rV","type":"tool_result","content":"     1‚Üí# Cloche Usage\n     2‚Üí\n     3‚ÜíCloche runs containerized workflows for autonomous coding agents. You define a\n     4‚Üíworkflow graph in the `.cloche` DSL, Cloche copies your project into a Docker\n     5‚Üícontainer, runs the workflow steps (agent prompts and shell scripts), and extracts\n     6‚Üíresults to a git branch.\n     7‚Üí\n     8‚Üí## Core Concepts\n     9‚Üí\n    10‚Üí- **Workflow**: A directed graph of steps connected by named-result wiring.\n    11‚Üí- **Step**: A unit of work. Type is inferred: `prompt` = agent step, `run` = script step, `workflow_name` = workflow step (host only).\n    12‚Üí- **Result**: A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. `success`, `fail`, `needs-research`). Steps declare their possible results; the engine follows wiring based on the reported result.\n    13‚Üí- **Wiring**: Maps `step:result` pairs to the next step. Separate from step definitions.\n    14‚Üí- **Terminals**: `done` (success) and `abort` (failure) are built-in terminal targets.\n    15‚Üí\n    16‚Üí## Workflow DSL\n    17‚Üí\n    18‚ÜíWorkflow files use the `.cloche` extension and live in `.cloche/`. The first step\n    19‚Üídeclared is the entry point. Graphs are validated at parse time (all results wired,\n    20‚Üíno orphans, entry point exists).\n    21‚Üí\n    22‚Üí### Minimal Example\n    23‚Üí\n    24‚Üí```\n    25‚Üíworkflow \"develop\" {\n    26‚Üí  step implement {\n    27‚Üí    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    28‚Üí    results = [success, fail]\n    29‚Üí  }\n    30‚Üí\n    31‚Üí  step test {\n    32‚Üí    run = \"make test 2>&1\"\n    33‚Üí    results = [success, fail]\n    34‚Üí  }\n    35‚Üí\n    36‚Üí  implement:success -> test\n    37‚Üí  implement:fail -> abort\n    38‚Üí  test:success -> done\n    39‚Üí  test:fail -> abort\n    40‚Üí}\n    41‚Üí```\n    42‚Üí\n    43‚Üí### Step Configuration\n    44‚Üí\n    45‚Üí| Key | Type | Description |\n    46‚Üí|-----|------|-------------|\n    47‚Üí| `prompt` | string or `file(\"path\")` | Prompt template. Makes this an agent step. |\n    48‚Üí| `run` | string | Shell command. Makes this a script step. |\n    49‚Üí| `workflow_name` | string | Container workflow to dispatch. Makes this a workflow step (host only). |\n    50‚Üí| `results` | ident list | Declared result names, e.g. `[success, fail, give-up]`. |\n    51‚Üí| `max_attempts` | string | Max retries before automatic `give-up` result, e.g. `\"2\"`. |\n    52‚Üí| `timeout` | string | Step timeout as Go duration, e.g. `\"30m\"`, `\"2h\"`. Default: 30m. |\n    53‚Üí| `agent_command` | string | Agent binary name(s), comma-separated for fallback chains, e.g. `\"claude,gemini\"`. |\n    54‚Üí| `agent_args` | string | Override default agent arguments. |\n    55‚Üí| `feedback` | string | Set to `\"true\"` to include `.cloche/output/*.log` content in the prompt. |\n    56‚Üí| `prompt_step` | string | For workflow steps: which preceding step's output to use as the prompt. |\n    57‚Üí\n    58‚ÜíA step must have exactly one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`.\n    59‚Üí\n    60‚Üí### The `file()` Function\n    61‚Üí\n    62‚Üí`file(\"path\")` reads the file at the given path relative to the working directory\n    63‚Üí(`/workspace/` in containers) at execution time, not parse time. Use it for prompt\n    64‚Üítemplates:\n    65‚Üí\n    66‚Üí```\n    67‚Üíprompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    68‚Üí```\n    69‚Üí\n    70‚Üí### The `container {}` Block\n    71‚Üí\n    72‚ÜíCan appear at step level or workflow level. Keys are stored with a `container.` prefix.\n    73‚Üí\n    74‚Üí**Step level** ‚Äî per-step container config:\n    75‚Üí```\n    76‚Üístep code {\n    77‚Üí  prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    78‚Üí  container {\n    79‚Üí    image         = \"custom-agent:v2\"\n    80‚Üí    memory        = \"4g\"\n    81‚Üí    network_allow = [\"docs.python.org\", \"api.example.com\"]\n    82‚Üí  }\n    83‚Üí  results = [success, fail]\n    84‚Üí}\n    85‚Üí```\n    86‚Üí\n    87‚Üí**Workflow level** ‚Äî defaults for all steps:\n    88‚Üí```\n    89‚Üíworkflow \"develop\" {\n    90‚Üí  container {\n    91‚Üí    agent_command = \"gemini\"\n    92‚Üí    image         = \"myregistry/myimage:v2\"\n    93‚Üí    memory        = \"4g\"\n    94‚Üí  }\n    95‚Üí  ...\n    96‚Üí}\n    97‚Üí```\n    98‚Üí\n    99‚ÜíSupported keys: `image`, `memory`, `network_allow`, `agent_command`, `agent_args`.\n   100‚Üí\n   101‚Üí### The `host {}` Block\n   102‚Üí\n   103‚ÜíCan appear at workflow level in host workflows (`.cloche/host.cloche`). Keys are stored\n   104‚Üíwith a `host.` prefix. Configures agent defaults for agent steps running on the host.\n   105‚Üí\n   106‚Üí```\n   107‚Üíworkflow \"main\" {\n   108‚Üí  host {\n   109‚Üí    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   110‚Üí  }\n   111‚Üí  ...\n   112‚Üí}\n   113‚Üí```\n   114‚Üí\n   115‚ÜíSupported keys: `agent_command`, `agent_args`. Step-level `agent_command` and\n   116‚Üí`agent_args` config keys override the workflow-level `host {}` defaults.\n   117‚Üí\n   118‚Üí### Wiring Syntax\n   119‚Üí\n   120‚ÜíConnect steps with `step:result -> next_step`:\n   121‚Üí\n   122‚Üí```\n   123‚Üíimplement:success -> test\n   124‚Üíimplement:fail -> abort\n   125‚Üítest:success -> done\n   126‚Üítest:fail -> fix\n   127‚Üí```\n   128‚Üí\n   129‚Üí### Wire Output Mappings\n   130‚Üí\n   131‚ÜíExtract values from a step's JSON output and inject as env vars into the target:\n   132‚Üí\n   133‚Üí```\n   134‚Üístep-a:success -> step-b [ ENV_VAR = output.field, OTHER = output.list[0].name ]\n   135‚Üí```\n   136‚Üí\n   137‚ÜíPath expressions:\n   138‚Üí\n   139‚Üí| Expression | Meaning |\n   140‚Üí|---|---|\n   141‚Üí| `output` | Raw output (full string) |\n   142‚Üí| `output.key` | JSON object field access |\n   143‚Üí| `output[N]` | JSON array index (0-based) |\n   144‚Üí| `output.a.b.c` | Deeply nested field access |\n   145‚Üí| `output.items[0].name` | Mixed field and index chaining |\n   146‚Üí\n   147‚ÜíIf the output is valid JSON, path expressions navigate the structure. If it's plain\n   148‚Üítext, only bare `output` works.\n   149‚Üí\n   150‚Üí### Retry Loops\n   151‚Üí\n   152‚ÜíWire failures back to earlier steps:\n   153‚Üí\n   154‚Üí```\n   155‚Üítest:fail -> fix\n   156‚Üífix:success -> test    // retry the test\n   157‚Üífix:fail -> abort\n   158‚Üí```\n   159‚Üí\n   160‚ÜíUse `max_attempts` to cap retries. When exhausted, the step returns `give-up`:\n   161‚Üí\n   162‚Üí```\n   163‚Üístep fix {\n   164‚Üí  prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/fix.md\")\n   165‚Üí  max_attempts = \"2\"\n   166‚Üí  results = [success, fail, give-up]\n   167‚Üí}\n   168‚Üí```\n   169‚Üí\n   170‚Üí### Parallel Branches (Fanout)\n   171‚Üí\n   172‚ÜíWire one result to multiple targets for concurrent execution:\n   173‚Üí\n   174‚Üí```\n   175‚Üítest:success -> lint\n   176‚Üítest:success -> quality\n   177‚Üí```\n   178‚Üí\n   179‚Üí### Collect (Join)\n   180‚Üí\n   181‚ÜíSynchronize parallel branches:\n   182‚Üí\n   183‚Üí```\n   184‚Üícollect all(lint:success, quality:success) -> done\n   185‚Üícollect any(lint:success, quality:success) -> done\n   186‚Üí```\n   187‚Üí\n   188‚Üí`all` fires when every condition is met. `any` fires when at least one is.\n   189‚Üí\n   190‚Üí### Comments\n   191‚Üí\n   192‚ÜíLine comments with `//`:\n   193‚Üí\n   194‚Üí```\n   195‚Üí// This is a comment\n   196‚Üíimplement:success -> test  // inline comment\n   197‚Üí```\n   198‚Üí\n   199‚Üí## Result Protocol\n   200‚Üí\n   201‚ÜíSteps report results by printing a marker line to stdout:\n   202‚Üí\n   203‚Üí```\n   204‚ÜíCLOCHE_RESULT:<name>\n   205‚Üí```\n   206‚Üí\n   207‚ÜíFor example: `CLOCHE_RESULT:success`, `CLOCHE_RESULT:needs-research`, `CLOCHE_RESULT:give-up`.\n   208‚Üí\n   209‚ÜíRules:\n   210‚Üí- The **last** `CLOCHE_RESULT:` line wins if multiple are printed.\n   211‚Üí- Marker lines are **stripped** from captured output (not passed to logs or downstream steps).\n   212‚Üí- The result name must match one of the step's declared `results`.\n   213‚Üí- For script steps with no marker: exit 0 = `success`, exit non-zero = `fail`.\n   214‚Üí- For agent steps: if exit non-zero with a marker, the marker result is used. If exit non-zero without a marker, falls back to the next agent in the fallback chain (or returns `fail` if last).\n   215‚Üí\n   216‚Üí## Prompt Assembly\n   217‚Üí\n   218‚ÜíWhen an agent step runs, Cloche assembles a prompt from these sections (joined by blank lines):\n   219‚Üí\n   220‚Üí1. **Step template**: The step's `prompt` content (inline string or resolved `file(\"path\")`).\n   221‚Üí2. **User request**: Content of `.cloche/<run-id>/prompt.txt` (set via `--prompt` flag), prefixed with `## User Request`.\n   222‚Üí3. **Validation output** (opt-in): If `feedback = \"true\"`, reads all `.log` files from `.cloche/output/` and includes them prefixed with `## Validation Output`.\n   223‚Üí4. **Result selection**: Lists the step's declared results with instructions to print exactly one `CLOCHE_RESULT:<name>` marker.\n   224‚Üí\n   225‚ÜíThe assembled prompt is passed to the agent command via stdin.\n   226‚Üí\n   227‚Üí## Agent Command Resolution\n   228‚Üí\n   229‚ÜíPriority (highest to lowest):\n   230‚Üí1. Step-level `agent_command`\n   231‚Üí2. Workflow-level config block (`container { agent_command }` for container workflows, `host { agent_command }` for host workflows)\n   232‚Üí3. `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` environment variable\n   233‚Üí4. Default: `claude`\n   234‚Üí\n   235‚Üí### Fallback Chains\n   236‚Üí\n   237‚ÜíComma-separated commands are tried in order:\n   238‚Üí\n   239‚Üí```\n   240‚Üíagent_command = \"claude,gemini,codex\"\n   241‚Üí```\n   242‚Üí\n   243‚Üí- **Command not found / failed to start** ‚Äî try next command\n   244‚Üí- **Exit non-zero without `CLOCHE_RESULT` marker** ‚Äî try next command\n   245‚Üí- **Exit non-zero with `CLOCHE_RESULT` marker** ‚Äî use that result (no fallback)\n   246‚Üí- **Exit 0** ‚Äî use result (no fallback)\n   247‚Üí- **All commands fail to start** ‚Äî step returns an error\n   248‚Üí- **Last command crashes without marker** ‚Äî step returns `fail`\n   249‚Üí\n   250‚ÜíKnown agents (e.g. `claude`) get default arguments (`-p --output-format stream-json --verbose --dangerously-skip-permissions`). Unknown agents receive the prompt on stdin with no flags. Override with `agent_args`.\n   251‚Üí\n   252‚Üí### Agent Setup Guides\n   253‚Üí\n   254‚ÜíFor detailed container setup instructions per agent:\n   255‚Üí\n   256‚Üí- [How to set up Claude Code](agent-setup-claude.md) ‚Äî session-based auth, no API key needed\n   257‚Üí- [How to set up Codex](agent-setup-codex.md) ‚Äî API key configuration\n   258‚Üí\n   259‚Üí## Workflow Locations\n   260‚Üí\n   261‚Üí**Container workflows** (`.cloche/*.cloche` except `host.cloche`) run inside Docker\n   262‚Üívia `cloche-agent`. Steps may only be `agent` or `script` type.\n   263‚Üí\n   264‚Üí**Host workflow** (`.cloche/host.cloche`) runs on the host machine as the daemon.\n   265‚ÜíSteps may be `agent`, `script`, or `workflow` type. The `workflow_name` step type\n   266‚Üídispatches a container workflow run and blocks until it completes. Script steps\n   267‚Üíexecute with their working directory set to the main git worktree, so host-workflow\n   268‚Üífixes on main are available to in-flight runs even if they branched earlier.\n   269‚Üí\n   270‚ÜíA single `host.cloche` file may contain **multiple named workflows**. The daemon\n   271‚Üíuses up to three workflow phases for orchestration:\n   272‚Üí\n   273‚Üí| Phase | Workflow name | Purpose |\n   274‚Üí|-------|--------------|---------|\n   275‚Üí| 1 | `list-tasks` | Discover available work. Output is JSONL (one task per line). |\n   276‚Üí| 2 | `main` | Do the work. Receives a task ID via `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` env var. |\n   277‚Üí| 3 | `finalize` | Post-main cleanup. Runs on **both** success and failure. |\n   278‚Üí\n   279‚ÜíOnly `main` is required. If `list-tasks` is absent, the daemon uses a single-workflow\n   280‚Üímode. If `finalize` is absent, it is skipped.\n   281‚Üí\n   282‚Üí### list-tasks Output Format\n   283‚Üí\n   284‚ÜíThe `list-tasks` workflow's final step output is parsed as JSONL. Each line is a JSON\n   285‚Üíobject:\n   286‚Üí\n   287‚Üí| Field | Required | Description |\n   288‚Üí|-------|----------|-------------|\n   289‚Üí| `id` | yes | Unique task identifier |\n   290‚Üí| `status` | yes | One of `open`, `closed`, `in-progress` |\n   291‚Üí| `title` | no | Short summary |\n   292‚Üí| `description` | no | Full description |\n   293‚Üí| `metadata` | no | Arbitrary key-value pairs |\n   294‚Üí\n   295‚ÜíThe daemon picks the first task with status `open`, runs `main` with that task's ID\n   296‚Üíset in `CLOCHE_TASK_ID`, then runs `finalize` with the outcome. Tasks are\n   297‚Üídeduplicated within a timeout window to prevent rapid reassignment of the same task.\n   298‚Üí\n   299‚Üí### Host Workflow Example\n   300‚Üí\n   301‚ÜíA three-phase `host.cloche`:\n   302‚Üí\n   303‚Üí```\n   304‚Üíworkflow \"list-tasks\" {\n   305‚Üí  step fetch-tickets {\n   306‚Üí    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n   307‚Üí    results = [success, fail]\n   308‚Üí  }\n   309‚Üí\n   310‚Üí  fetch-tickets:success -> done\n   311‚Üí  fetch-tickets:fail    -> abort\n   312‚Üí}\n   313‚Üí\n   314‚Üíworkflow \"main\" {\n   315‚Üí  host {\n   316‚Üí    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   317‚Üí  }\n   318‚Üí\n   319‚Üí  step prepare-prompt {\n   320‚Üí    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n   321‚Üí    results = [success, fail]\n   322‚Üí  }\n   323‚Üí\n   324‚Üí  step develop {\n   325‚Üí    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n   326‚Üí    results       = [success, fail]\n   327‚Üí  }\n   328‚Üí\n   329‚Üí  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n   330‚Üí  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n   331‚Üí  develop:success        -> done\n   332‚Üí  develop:fail           -> done\n   333‚Üí}\n   334‚Üí\n   335‚Üíworkflow \"finalize\" {\n   336‚Üí  step push-for-review {\n   337‚Üí    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/push-for-review.sh\"\n   338‚Üí    results = [success, fail]\n   339‚Üí  }\n   340‚Üí\n   341‚Üí  push-for-review:success -> done\n   342‚Üí  push-for-review:fail    -> done\n   343‚Üí}\n   344‚Üí```\n   345‚Üí\n   346‚ÜíThe `list-tasks` script writes JSONL to `$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`. The `main` workflow\n   347‚Üíreceives the task ID and is responsible for claiming the ticket. The `finalize`\n   348‚Üíworkflow receives `CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` env vars to decide\n   349‚Üíwhat cleanup to perform.\n   350‚Üí\n   351‚Üí### Host Step Environment Variables\n   352‚Üí\n   353‚Üí| Variable | Description |\n   354‚Üí|----------|-------------|\n   355‚Üí| `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` | Absolute path to the project directory on the host. |\n   356‚Üí| `CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT` | Path where this step should write its output (for output mappings). |\n   357‚Üí| `CLOCHE_PREV_OUTPUT` | Path to the output file from the immediately preceding step. |\n   358‚Üí| `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` | The run ID for this workflow execution. |\n   359‚Üí| `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` | Task ID assigned by the daemon (set for `main` and `finalize` phases). |\n   360‚Üí| `CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` | Result of the `main` workflow (`succeeded` or `failed`). Set for `finalize` phase only. |\n   361‚Üí| `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` | Run ID of the completed `main` workflow. Set for `finalize` phase only. |\n   362‚Üí| Wire-mapped vars | Any env vars declared in wire output mappings. |\n   363‚Üí\n   364‚Üí### Container Environment Variables\n   365‚Üí\n   366‚Üí| Variable | Description |\n   367‚Üí|----------|-------------|\n   368‚Üí| `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` | The run ID for this workflow execution. |\n   369‚Üí| `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` | Working directory (set for script steps so `cloche get`/`cloche set` work). |\n   370‚Üí| `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` | Passed through from the host if set. |\n   371‚Üí| `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` | Overrides the default agent command inside the container. |\n   372‚Üí\n   373‚Üí## Complete Example: Container Workflow with Parallel Validation\n   374‚Üí\n   375‚Üí```\n   376‚Üíworkflow \"develop\" {\n   377‚Üí  step implement {\n   378‚Üí    prompt = file(\"prompts/implement.md\")\n   379‚Üí    results = [success, fail]\n   380‚Üí  }\n   381‚Üí\n   382‚Üí  step test {\n   383‚Üí    run = \"bundle exec rake test 2>&1\"\n   384‚Üí    results = [success, fail]\n   385‚Üí  }\n   386‚Üí\n   387‚Üí  step lint {\n   388‚Üí    run = \"bundle exec rubocop 2>&1\"\n   389‚Üí    results = [success, fail]\n   390‚Üí  }\n   391‚Üí\n   392‚Üí  step quality {\n   393‚Üí    run = \"python3 scripts/quality-check.py 2>&1\"\n   394‚Üí    results = [success, fail]\n   395‚Üí  }\n   396‚Üí\n   397‚Üí  step fix {\n   398‚Üí    prompt = file(\"prompts/fix.md\")\n   399‚Üí    max_attempts = \"2\"\n   400‚Üí    results = [success, fail, give-up]\n   401‚Üí  }\n   402‚Üí\n   403‚Üí  implement:success -> test\n   404‚Üí  implement:fail -> abort\n   405‚Üí\n   406‚Üí  test:success -> lint\n   407‚Üí  test:success -> quality\n   408‚Üí  test:fail -> fix\n   409‚Üí\n   410‚Üí  lint:fail -> fix\n   411‚Üí  quality:fail -> fix\n   412‚Üí  collect all(lint:success, quality:success) -> done\n   413‚Üí\n   414‚Üí  fix:success -> test\n   415‚Üí  fix:fail -> abort\n   416‚Üí  fix:give-up -> abort\n   417‚Üí}\n   418‚Üí```\n   419‚Üí\n   420‚Üí## Container Isolation Model\n   421‚Üí\n   422‚Üí- **Files in**: `docker cp` copies the project into `/workspace/`. No bind mounts. Override files from `.cloche/overrides/` are applied on top. `.git/` is included.\n   423‚Üí- **Files out**: On completion, the daemon extracts results via `docker cp` into a git worktree and commits to a `cloche/<run-id>` branch.\n   424‚Üí- **Auth files**: `~/.claude/` and `~/.claude.json` are copied into each container at `/home/agent/` for Claude Code session reuse. Copied (not bind-mounted) so each container gets its own isolated copy.\n   425‚Üí- **Network**: Containers have network access (needed for API calls).\n   426‚Üí- **Cleanup**: Containers are removed after successful runs unless `--keep-container` is set. Failed runs always keep their container.\n   427‚Üí\n   428‚ÜíYour project directory is never modified by the container.\n   429‚Üí\n   430‚Üí## CLI Reference\n   431‚Üí\n   432‚ÜíEvery subcommand supports `--help` (or `-h`) to show detailed usage, flags, and\n   433‚Üíexamples. Use `cloche help <command>` for the same output:\n   434‚Üí\n   435‚Üí```\n   436‚Üícloche --help              # top-level overview\n   437‚Üícloche help run            # detailed help for \"run\"\n   438‚Üícloche run --help          # same as above\n   439‚Üí```\n   440‚Üí\n   441‚Üí### `cloche init`\n   442‚Üí\n   443‚ÜíScaffold a new Cloche project.\n   444‚Üí\n   445‚Üí```\n   446‚Üícloche init [--workflow <name>] [--base-image <base>]\n   447‚Üí```\n   448‚Üí\n   449‚Üí| Flag | Default | Description |\n   450‚Üí|------|---------|-------------|\n   451‚Üí| `--workflow <name>` | `develop` | Workflow name. Creates `.cloche/<name>.cloche`. |\n   452‚Üí| `--base-image <base>` | `cloche-base:latest` | Base Docker image for the generated Dockerfile. |\n   453‚Üí\n   454‚ÜíCreates `.cloche/` with workflow file, Dockerfile, `config.toml`, prompt templates,\n   455‚Üíhost workflow (`host.cloche`), and prompt generation script. Skips existing files.\n   456‚Üí\n   457‚Üí### `cloche run`\n   458‚Üí\n   459‚ÜíLaunch a workflow run.\n   460‚Üí\n   461‚Üí```\n   462‚Üícloche run --workflow <name> [--prompt \"...\"] [--title \"...\"] [--keep-container]\n   463‚Üí```\n   464‚Üí\n   465‚Üí| Flag | Description |\n   466‚Üí|------|-------------|\n   467‚Üí| `--workflow <name>` | Workflow name. Resolves to `.cloche/<name>.cloche`. |\n   468‚Üí| `--prompt \"...\"`, `-p` | Inline prompt written to `.cloche/<run-id>/prompt.txt`. |\n   469‚Üí| `--title \"...\"` | One-line summary for status display. Auto-generated if omitted. |\n   470‚Üí| `--keep-container` | Keep container on success (failed runs always keep it). |\n   471‚Üí\n   472‚ÜíMust be run from inside a git repository. The daemon auto-rebuilds the Docker image\n   473‚Üíwhen `.cloche/Dockerfile` changes.\n   474‚Üí\n   475‚Üí### `cloche status`\n   476‚Üí\n   477‚Üí```\n   478‚Üícloche status <run-id>\n   479‚Üí```\n   480‚Üí\n   481‚ÜíShows run title, type (`host`/`container`), state, active steps, and per-step results.\n   482‚Üí\n   483‚Üí### `cloche list`\n   484‚Üí\n   485‚Üí```\n   486‚Üícloche list [--all]\n   487‚Üí```\n   488‚Üí\n   489‚ÜíLists runs for the current project directory. Pass `--all` to show runs across all projects.\n   490‚Üí\n   491‚Üí### `cloche logs`\n   492‚Üí\n   493‚Üí```\n   494‚Üícloche logs <run-id> [--step <name>] [--type <full|script|llm>] [-f]\n   495‚Üí```\n   496‚Üí\n   497‚Üí| Flag | Description |\n   498‚Üí|------|-------------|\n   499‚Üí| `--step <name>` | Show only logs for the specified step. |\n   500‚Üí| `--type <full\\|script\\|llm>` | Log type filter. |\n   501‚Üí| `-f` | Follow mode: display existing logs then continue streaming new lines as they arrive (like `tail -f`). |\n   502‚Üí\n   503‚ÜíWithout `-f`, displays all logs captured to date and exits (even for active runs). With `-f` on an active run, existing logs are sent first, then new output is streamed in real time via gRPC until the run completes.\n   504‚Üí\n   505‚Üí### `cloche poll`\n   506‚Üí\n   507‚Üí```\n   508‚Üícloche poll <run-id>\n   509‚Üí```\n   510‚Üí\n   511‚ÜíBlock until the run finishes. Polls every 2 seconds. Exits 0 on success, 1 on failure.\n   512‚Üí\n   513‚Üí### `cloche stop`\n   514‚Üí\n   515‚Üí```\n   516‚Üícloche stop <run-id>\n   517‚Üí```\n   518‚Üí\n   519‚Üí### `cloche delete`\n   520‚Üí\n   521‚Üí```\n   522‚Üícloche delete <container-or-run-id>\n   523‚Üí```\n   524‚Üí\n   525‚ÜíDelete a retained Docker container by container ID or run ID.\n   526‚Üí\n   527‚Üí### `cloche health`\n   528‚Üí\n   529‚Üí```\n   530‚Üícloche health\n   531‚Üí```\n   532‚Üí\n   533‚ÜíShow per-project pass/fail summary. Requires `CLOCHE_HTTP`.\n   534‚Üí\n   535‚Üí### `cloche get`\n   536‚Üí\n   537‚Üí```\n   538‚Üícloche get <key>\n   539‚Üí```\n   540‚Üí\n   541‚ÜíGet a value from the run context store (`.cloche/<run-id>/context.json`). Requires\n   542‚Üíthe `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` environment variable. Uses `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` if set, otherwise\n   543‚Üíthe current working directory. Exits 1 if the key is not found.\n   544‚Üí\n   545‚Üí### `cloche set`\n   546‚Üí\n   547‚Üí```\n   548‚Üícloche set <key> <value|->\n   549‚Üí```\n   550‚Üí\n   551‚ÜíSet a value in the run context store (`.cloche/<run-id>/context.json`). Requires\n   552‚Üíthe `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` environment variable. Uses `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` if set, otherwise\n   553‚Üíthe current working directory. Creates the file and directories if they don't exist.\n   554‚ÜíPass `-` as the value to read from stdin (trailing newlines are trimmed).\n   555‚Üí\n   556‚Üí### `cloche tasks`\n   557‚Üí\n   558‚Üí```\n   559‚Üícloche tasks [--project <dir>]\n   560‚Üí```\n   561‚Üí\n   562‚ÜíShow the task pipeline and assignment state for an orchestration loop. Displays\n   563‚Üíupcoming/open tasks, which tasks are assigned to which runs, and auto-assignment\n   564‚Üístate. Requires `CLOCHE_HTTP` (talks to the daemon's web API).\n   565‚Üí\n   566‚Üí| Flag | Default | Description |\n   567‚Üí|------|---------|-------------|\n   568‚Üí| `--project <dir>` | current directory name | Project to query tasks for. |\n   569‚Üí\n   570‚Üí### `cloche loop`\n   571‚Üí\n   572‚ÜíStart or stop the daemon's orchestration loop. The loop automatically picks up\n   573‚Üítasks from the pipeline and runs them.\n   574‚Üí\n   575‚Üí```\n   576‚Üícloche loop [--max <n>]\n   577‚Üícloche loop stop\n   578‚Üí```\n   579‚Üí\n   580‚Üí| Flag | Default | Description |\n   581‚Üí|------|---------|-------------|\n   582‚Üí| `--max <n>` | config value | Maximum concurrent runs. Defaults to the value in `.cloche/config.toml`. |\n   583‚Üí\n   584‚Üí`cloche loop stop` disables the loop. Running tasks are not cancelled.\n   585‚Üí\n   586‚Üí### `cloche shutdown`\n   587‚Üí\n   588‚Üí```\n   589‚Üícloche shutdown\n   590‚Üí```\n   591‚Üí\n   592‚Üí## Project Layout\n   593‚Üí\n   594‚Üí```\n   595‚Üímy-project/\n   596‚Üí‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ .cloche/\n   597‚Üí‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ develop.cloche        # Container workflow\n   598‚Üí‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ host.cloche           # Host orchestration workflow\n   599‚Üí‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ Dockerfile            # Container image definition\n   600‚Üí‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ config.toml           # Project configuration\n   601‚Üí‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ prompts/              # Prompt templates\n   602‚Üí‚îÇ   ‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ implement.md\n   603‚Üí‚îÇ   ‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ fix.md\n   604‚Üí‚îÇ   ‚îÇ   ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ update-docs.md\n   605‚Üí‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ scripts/              # Host-side scripts\n   606‚Üí‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ overrides/            # Files copied on top of /workspace/\n   607‚Üí‚îÇ   ‚îÇ   ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ CLAUDE.md         # Container-specific CLAUDE.md (optional)\n   608‚Üí‚îÇ   ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ <run-id>/             # Runtime state (gitignored)\n   609‚Üí‚îÇ       ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ prompt.txt        # User prompt\n   610‚Üí‚îÇ       ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ context.json      # Shared key-value store (cloche get/set)\n   611‚Üí‚îÇ       ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ output/\n   612‚Üí‚îÇ       ‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ full.log      # Unified log\n   613‚Üí‚îÇ       ‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ test.log      # Per-step script output\n   614‚Üí‚îÇ       ‚îÇ   ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ llm-impl.log  # Per-step LLM conversation\n   615‚Üí‚îÇ       ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ attempt_count/    # Retry counters for max_attempts\n   616‚Üí‚îÇ       ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ history.log       # Step execution log\n   617‚Üí‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ src/                      # Project source (untouched by Cloche)\n   618‚Üí‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ .git/\n   619‚Üí```\n   620‚Üí\n   621‚Üí## Daemon Configuration\n   622‚Üí\n   623‚Üí| Variable | Default | Description |\n   624‚Üí|----------|---------|-------------|\n   625‚Üí| `CLOCHE_LISTEN` | `unix:///tmp/cloche.sock` | Listen address |\n   626‚Üí| `CLOCHE_DB` | `cloche.db` | SQLite database path |\n   627‚Üí| `CLOCHE_RUNTIME` | `docker` | `docker` or `local` (subprocess, for dev only) |\n   628‚Üí| `CLOCHE_IMAGE` | `cloche-agent:latest` | Default Docker image |\n   629‚Üí| `CLOCHE_HTTP` | _(unset)_ | HTTP address for web dashboard. Not started unless set. |\n   630‚Üí| `CLOCHE_AGENT_PATH` | _(auto)_ | Path to `cloche-agent` binary (local runtime) |\n   631‚Üí| `CLOCHE_LLM_COMMAND` | _(unset)_ | Command for LLM calls (evolution, merge conflicts) |\n   632‚Üí| `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` | _(unset)_ | Passed into Docker containers |\n   633‚Üí| `CLOCHE_EXTRA_MOUNTS` | _(unset)_ | Extra bind mounts (comma-separated `host:container`) |\n   634‚Üí| `CLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV` | _(unset)_ | Extra env vars (comma-separated `KEY=VALUE`) |\n   635‚Üí\n   636‚Üí### Client Configuration\n   637‚Üí\n   638‚Üí| Variable | Default | Description |\n   639‚Üí|----------|---------|-------------|\n   640‚Üí| `CLOCHE_ADDR` | `unix:///tmp/cloche.sock` | Daemon gRPC address |\n   641‚Üí| `CLOCHE_HTTP` | `localhost:8080` | Daemon HTTP address |\n   642‚Üí\n   643‚Üí## Dockerfile Requirements\n   644‚Üí\n   645‚ÜíThe container image must have:\n   646‚Üí- `cloche-agent` binary at `/usr/local/bin/cloche-agent`\n   647‚Üí- `git` installed\n   648‚Üí- An `agent` user (cloche wraps commands with `chown` + `su agent`)\n   649‚Üí- `/workspace` as the working directory\n   650‚Üí- Your project's build dependencies and the agent binary (e.g. `claude`)\n   651‚Üí\n   652‚Üí## Build Commands\n   653‚Üí\n   654‚Üí```\n   655‚Üímake build          # Build all binaries to bin/\n   656‚Üímake test           # Run all tests\n   657‚Üímake test-short     # Run tests (skip slow ones)\n   658‚Üímake lint           # Run go vet\n   659‚Üímake proto          # Regenerate gRPC code from protobuf\n   660‚Üímake docker-build   # Build the cloche-agent Docker image\n   661‚Üímake install        # Build, install to ~/.local/bin/, restart daemon\n   662‚Üímake clean          # Remove bin/\n   663‚Üí```\n   664‚Üí"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2090add2-0fe6-4270-9f3b-b52deb6bac91","uuid":"d5af902a-37a6-416f-a965-5f50a5f800b1","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/docs/USAGE.md","content":"# Cloche Usage\n\nCloche runs containerized workflows for autonomous coding agents. You define a\nworkflow graph in the `.cloche` DSL, Cloche copies your project into a Docker\ncontainer, runs the workflow steps (agent prompts and shell scripts), and extracts\nresults to a git branch.\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n- **Workflow**: A directed graph of steps connected by named-result wiring.\n- **Step**: A unit of work. Type is inferred: `prompt` = agent step, `run` = script step, `workflow_name` = workflow step (host only).\n- **Result**: A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. `success`, `fail`, `needs-research`). Steps declare their possible results; the engine follows wiring based on the reported result.\n- **Wiring**: Maps `step:result` pairs to the next step. Separate from step definitions.\n- **Terminals**: `done` (success) and `abort` (failure) are built-in terminal targets.\n\n## Workflow DSL\n\nWorkflow files use the `.cloche` extension and live in `.cloche/`. The first step\ndeclared is the entry point. Graphs are validated at parse time (all results wired,\nno orphans, entry point exists).\n\n### Minimal Example\n\n```\nworkflow \"develop\" {\n  step implement {\n    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step test {\n    run = \"make test 2>&1\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  implement:success -> test\n  implement:fail -> abort\n  test:success -> done\n  test:fail -> abort\n}\n```\n\n### Step Configuration\n\n| Key | Type | Description |\n|-----|------|-------------|\n| `prompt` | string or `file(\"path\")` | Prompt template. Makes this an agent step. |\n| `run` | string | Shell command. Makes this a script step. |\n| `workflow_name` | string | Container workflow to dispatch. Makes this a workflow step (host only). |\n| `results` | ident list | Declared result names, e.g. `[success, fail, give-up]`. |\n| `max_attempts` | string | Max retries before automatic `give-up` result, e.g. `\"2\"`. |\n| `timeout` | string | Step timeout as Go duration, e.g. `\"30m\"`, `\"2h\"`. Default: 30m. |\n| `agent_command` | string | Agent binary name(s), comma-separated for fallback chains, e.g. `\"claude,gemini\"`. |\n| `agent_args` | string | Override default agent arguments. |\n| `feedback` | string | Set to `\"true\"` to include `.cloche/output/*.log` content in the prompt. |\n| `prompt_step` | string | For workflow steps: which preceding step's output to use as the prompt. |\n\nA step must have exactly one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`.\n\n### The `file()` Function\n\n`file(\"path\")` reads the file at the given path relative to the working directory\n(`/workspace/` in containers) at execution time, not parse time. Use it for prompt\ntemplates:\n\n```\nprompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n```\n\n### The `container {}` Block\n\nCan appear at step level or workflow level. Keys are stored with a `container.` prefix.\n\n**Step level** ‚Äî per-step container config:\n```\nstep code {\n  prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n  container {\n    image         = \"custom-agent:v2\"\n    memory        = \"4g\"\n    network_allow = [\"docs.python.org\", \"api.example.com\"]\n  }\n  results = [success, fail]\n}\n```\n\n**Workflow level** ‚Äî defaults for all steps:\n```\nworkflow \"develop\" {\n  container {\n    agent_command = \"gemini\"\n    image         = \"myregistry/myimage:v2\"\n    memory        = \"4g\"\n  }\n  ...\n}\n```\n\nSupported keys: `image`, `memory`, `network_allow`, `agent_command`, `agent_args`.\n\n### The `host {}` Block\n\nCan appear at workflow level in host workflows (`.cloche/host.cloche`). Keys are stored\nwith a `host.` prefix. Configures agent defaults for agent steps running on the host.\n\n```\nworkflow \"main\" {\n  host {\n    agent_command = \"claude\"\n  }\n  ...\n}\n```\n\nSupported keys: `agent_command`, `agent_args`. Step-level `agent_command` and\n`agent_args` config keys override the workflow-level `host {}` defaults.\n\n### Wiring Syntax\n\nConnect steps with `step:result -> next_step`:\n\n```\nimplement:success -> test\nimplement:fail -> abort\ntest:success -> done\ntest:fail -> fix\n```\n\n### Wire Output Mappings\n\nExtract values from a step's JSON output and inject as env vars into the target:\n\n```\nstep-a:success -> step-b [ ENV_VAR = output.field, OTHER = output.list[0].name ]\n```\n\nPath expressions:\n\n| Expression | Meaning |\n|---|---|\n| `output` | Raw output (full string) |\n| `output.key` | JSON object field access |\n| `output[N]` | JSON array index (0-based) |\n| `output.a.b.c` | Deeply nested field access |\n| `output.items[0].name` | Mixed field and index chaining |\n\nIf the output is valid JSON, path expressions navigate the structure. If it's plain\ntext, only bare `output` works.\n\n### Retry Loops\n\nWire failures back to earlier steps:\n\n```\ntest:fail -> fix\nfix:success -> test    // retry the test\nfix:fail -> abort\n```\n\nUse `max_attempts` to cap retries. When exhausted, the step returns `give-up`:\n\n```\nstep fix {\n  prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/fix.md\")\n  max_attempts = \"2\"\n  results = [success, fail, give-up]\n}\n```\n\n### Parallel Branches (Fanout)\n\nWire one result to multiple targets for concurrent execution:\n\n```\ntest:success -> lint\ntest:success -> quality\n```\n\n### Collect (Join)\n\nSynchronize parallel branches:\n\n```\ncollect all(lint:success, quality:success) -> done\ncollect any(lint:success, quality:success) -> done\n```\n\n`all` fires when every condition is met. `any` fires when at least one is.\n\n### Comments\n\nLine comments with `//`:\n\n```\n// This is a comment\nimplement:success -> test  // inline comment\n```\n\n## Result Protocol\n\nSteps report results by printing a marker line to stdout:\n\n```\nCLOCHE_RESULT:<name>\n```\n\nFor example: `CLOCHE_RESULT:success`, `CLOCHE_RESULT:needs-research`, `CLOCHE_RESULT:give-up`.\n\nRules:\n- The **last** `CLOCHE_RESULT:` line wins if multiple are printed.\n- Marker lines are **stripped** from captured output (not passed to logs or downstream steps).\n- The result name must match one of the step's declared `results`.\n- For script steps with no marker: exit 0 = `success`, exit non-zero = `fail`.\n- For agent steps: if exit non-zero with a marker, the marker result is used. If exit non-zero without a marker, falls back to the next agent in the fallback chain (or returns `fail` if last).\n\n## Prompt Assembly\n\nWhen an agent step runs, Cloche assembles a prompt from these sections (joined by blank lines):\n\n1. **Step template**: The step's `prompt` content (inline string or resolved `file(\"path\")`).\n2. **User request**: Content of `.cloche/<run-id>/prompt.txt` (set via `--prompt` flag), prefixed with `## User Request`.\n3. **Validation output** (opt-in): If `feedback = \"true\"`, reads all `.log` files from `.cloche/output/` and includes them prefixed with `## Validation Output`.\n4. **Result selection**: Lists the step's declared results with instructions to print exactly one `CLOCHE_RESULT:<name>` marker.\n\nThe assembled prompt is passed to the agent command via stdin.\n\n## Agent Command Resolution\n\nPriority (highest to lowest):\n1. Step-level `agent_command`\n2. Workflow-level config block (`container { agent_command }` for container workflows, `host { agent_command }` for host workflows)\n3. `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` environment variable\n4. Default: `claude`\n\n### Fallback Chains\n\nComma-separated commands are tried in order:\n\n```\nagent_command = \"claude,gemini,codex\"\n```\n\n- **Command not found / failed to start** ‚Äî try next command\n- **Exit non-zero without `CLOCHE_RESULT` marker** ‚Äî try next command\n- **Exit non-zero with `CLOCHE_RESULT` marker** ‚Äî use that result (no fallback)\n- **Exit 0** ‚Äî use result (no fallback)\n- **All commands fail to start** ‚Äî step returns an error\n- **Last command crashes without marker** ‚Äî step returns `fail`\n\nKnown agents (e.g. `claude`) get default arguments (`-p --output-format stream-json --verbose --dangerously-skip-permissions`). Unknown agents receive the prompt on stdin with no flags. Override with `agent_args`.\n\n### Agent Setup Guides\n\nFor detailed container setup instructions per agent:\n\n- [How to set up Claude Code](agent-setup-claude.md) ‚Äî session-based auth, no API key needed\n- [How to set up Codex](agent-setup-codex.md) ‚Äî API key configuration\n\n## Workflow Locations\n\n**Container workflows** (`.cloche/*.cloche` except `host.cloche`) run inside Docker\nvia `cloche-agent`. Steps may only be `agent` or `script` type.\n\n**Host workflow** (`.cloche/host.cloche`) runs on the host machine as the daemon.\nSteps may be `agent`, `script`, or `workflow` type. The `workflow_name` step type\ndispatches a container workflow run and blocks until it completes. Script steps\nexecute with their working directory set to the main git worktree, so host-workflow\nfixes on main are available to in-flight runs even if they branched earlier.\n\nA single `host.cloche` file may contain **multiple named workflows**. The daemon\nuses up to three workflow phases for orchestration:\n\n| Phase | Workflow name | Purpose |\n|-------|--------------|---------|\n| 1 | `list-tasks` | Discover available work. Output is JSONL (one task per line). |\n| 2 | `main` | Do the work. Receives a task ID via `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` env var. |\n| 3 | `finalize` | Post-main cleanup. Runs on **both** success and failure. |\n\nOnly `main` is required. If `list-tasks` is absent, the daemon uses a single-workflow\nmode. If `finalize` is absent, it is skipped.\n\n### list-tasks Output Format\n\nThe `list-tasks` workflow's final step output is parsed as JSONL. Each line is a JSON\nobject:\n\n| Field | Required | Description |\n|-------|----------|-------------|\n| `id` | yes | Unique task identifier |\n| `status` | yes | One of `open`, `closed`, `in-progress` |\n| `title` | no | Short summary |\n| `description` | no | Full description |\n| `metadata` | no | Arbitrary key-value pairs |\n\nThe daemon picks the first task with status `open`, runs `main` with that task's ID\nset in `CLOCHE_TASK_ID`, then runs `finalize` with the outcome. Tasks are\ndeduplicated within a timeout window to prevent rapid reassignment of the same task.\n\n### Host Workflow Example\n\nA three-phase `host.cloche`:\n\n```\nworkflow \"list-tasks\" {\n  step fetch-tickets {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  fetch-tickets:success -> done\n  fetch-tickets:fail    -> abort\n}\n\nworkflow \"main\" {\n  host {\n    agent_command = \"claude\"\n  }\n\n  step prepare-prompt {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step develop {\n    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n    results       = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n  develop:success        -> done\n  develop:fail           -> done\n}\n\nworkflow \"finalize\" {\n  step push-for-review {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/push-for-review.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  push-for-review:success -> done\n  push-for-review:fail    -> done\n}\n```\n\nThe `list-tasks` script writes JSONL to `$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`. The `main` workflow\nreceives the task ID and is responsible for claiming the ticket. The `finalize`\nworkflow receives `CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` env vars to decide\nwhat cleanup to perform.\n\n### Host Step Environment Variables\n\n| Variable | Description |\n|----------|-------------|\n| `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` | Absolute path to the project directory on the host. |\n| `CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT` | Path where this step should write its output (for output mappings). |\n| `CLOCHE_PREV_OUTPUT` | Path to the output file from the immediately preceding step. |\n| `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` | The run ID for this workflow execution. |\n| `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` | Task ID assigned by the daemon (set for `main` and `finalize` phases). |\n| `CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` | Result of the `main` workflow (`succeeded` or `failed`). Set for `finalize` phase only. |\n| `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` | Run ID of the completed `main` workflow. Set for `finalize` phase only. |\n| Wire-mapped vars | Any env vars declared in wire output mappings. |\n\n### Container Environment Variables\n\n| Variable | Description |\n|----------|-------------|\n| `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` | The run ID for this workflow execution. |\n| `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` | Working directory (set for script steps so `cloche get`/`cloche set` work). |\n| `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` | Passed through from the host if set. |\n| `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` | Overrides the default agent command inside the container. |\n\n## Complete Example: Container Workflow with Parallel Validation\n\n```\nworkflow \"develop\" {\n  step implement {\n    prompt = file(\"prompts/implement.md\")\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step test {\n    run = \"bundle exec rake test 2>&1\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step lint {\n    run = \"bundle exec rubocop 2>&1\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step quality {\n    run = \"python3 scripts/quality-check.py 2>&1\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step fix {\n    prompt = file(\"prompts/fix.md\")\n    max_attempts = \"2\"\n    results = [success, fail, give-up]\n  }\n\n  implement:success -> test\n  implement:fail -> abort\n\n  test:success -> lint\n  test:success -> quality\n  test:fail -> fix\n\n  lint:fail -> fix\n  quality:fail -> fix\n  collect all(lint:success, quality:success) -> done\n\n  fix:success -> test\n  fix:fail -> abort\n  fix:give-up -> abort\n}\n```\n\n## Container Isolation Model\n\n- **Files in**: `docker cp` copies the project into `/workspace/`. No bind mounts. Override files from `.cloche/overrides/` are applied on top. `.git/` is included.\n- **Files out**: On completion, the daemon extracts results via `docker cp` into a git worktree and commits to a `cloche/<run-id>` branch.\n- **Auth files**: `~/.claude/` and `~/.claude.json` are copied into each container at `/home/agent/` for Claude Code session reuse. Copied (not bind-mounted) so each container gets its own isolated copy.\n- **Network**: Containers have network access (needed for API calls).\n- **Cleanup**: Containers are removed after successful runs unless `--keep-container` is set. Failed runs always keep their container.\n\nYour project directory is never modified by the container.\n\n## CLI Reference\n\nEvery subcommand supports `--help` (or `-h`) to show detailed usage, flags, and\nexamples. Use `cloche help <command>` for the same output:\n\n```\ncloche --help              # top-level overview\ncloche help run            # detailed help for \"run\"\ncloche run --help          # same as above\n```\n\n### `cloche init`\n\nScaffold a new Cloche project.\n\n```\ncloche init [--workflow <name>] [--base-image <base>]\n```\n\n| Flag | Default | Description |\n|------|---------|-------------|\n| `--workflow <name>` | `develop` | Workflow name. Creates `.cloche/<name>.cloche`. |\n| `--base-image <base>` | `cloche-base:latest` | Base Docker image for the generated Dockerfile. |\n\nCreates `.cloche/` with workflow file, Dockerfile, `config.toml`, prompt templates,\nhost workflow (`host.cloche`), and prompt generation script. Skips existing files.\n\n### `cloche run`\n\nLaunch a workflow run.\n\n```\ncloche run --workflow <name> [--prompt \"...\"] [--title \"...\"] [--keep-container]\n```\n\n| Flag | Description |\n|------|-------------|\n| `--workflow <name>` | Workflow name. Resolves to `.cloche/<name>.cloche`. |\n| `--prompt \"...\"`, `-p` | Inline prompt written to `.cloche/<run-id>/prompt.txt`. |\n| `--title \"...\"` | One-line summary for status display. Auto-generated if omitted. |\n| `--keep-container` | Keep container on success (failed runs always keep it). |\n\nMust be run from inside a git repository. The daemon auto-rebuilds the Docker image\nwhen `.cloche/Dockerfile` changes.\n\n### `cloche status`\n\n```\ncloche status <run-id>\n```\n\nShows run title, type (`host`/`container`), state, active steps, and per-step results.\n\n### `cloche list`\n\n```\ncloche list [--all]\n```\n\nLists runs for the current project directory. Pass `--all` to show runs across all projects.\n\n### `cloche logs`\n\n```\ncloche logs <run-id> [--step <name>] [--type <full|script|llm>] [-f]\n```\n\n| Flag | Description |\n|------|-------------|\n| `--step <name>` | Show only logs for the specified step. |\n| `--type <full\\|script\\|llm>` | Log type filter. |\n| `-f` | Follow mode: display existing logs then continue streaming new lines as they arrive (like `tail -f`). |\n\nWithout `-f`, displays all logs captured to date and exits (even for active runs). With `-f` on an active run, existing logs are sent first, then new output is streamed in real time via gRPC until the run completes.\n\n### `cloche poll`\n\n```\ncloche poll <run-id>\n```\n\nBlock until the run finishes. Polls every 2 seconds. Exits 0 on success, 1 on failure.\n\n### `cloche stop`\n\n```\ncloche stop <run-id>\n```\n\n### `cloche delete`\n\n```\ncloche delete <container-or-run-id>\n```\n\nDelete a retained Docker container by container ID or run ID.\n\n### `cloche health`\n\n```\ncloche health\n```\n\nShow per-project pass/fail summary. Requires `CLOCHE_HTTP`.\n\n### `cloche get`\n\n```\ncloche get <key>\n```\n\nGet a value from the run context store (`.cloche/<run-id>/context.json`). Requires\nthe `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` environment variable. Uses `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` if set, otherwise\nthe current working directory. Exits 1 if the key is not found.\n\n### `cloche set`\n\n```\ncloche set <key> <value|->\n```\n\nSet a value in the run context store (`.cloche/<run-id>/context.json`). Requires\nthe `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` environment variable. Uses `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` if set, otherwise\nthe current working directory. Creates the file and directories if they don't exist.\nPass `-` as the value to read from stdin (trailing newlines are trimmed).\n\n### `cloche tasks`\n\n```\ncloche tasks [--project <dir>]\n```\n\nShow the task pipeline and assignment state for an orchestration loop. Displays\nupcoming/open tasks, which tasks are assigned to which runs, and auto-assignment\nstate. Requires `CLOCHE_HTTP` (talks to the daemon's web API).\n\n| Flag | Default | Description |\n|------|---------|-------------|\n| `--project <dir>` | current directory name | Project to query tasks for. |\n\n### `cloche loop`\n\nStart or stop the daemon's orchestration loop. The loop automatically picks up\ntasks from the pipeline and runs them.\n\n```\ncloche loop [--max <n>]\ncloche loop stop\n```\n\n| Flag | Default | Description |\n|------|---------|-------------|\n| `--max <n>` | config value | Maximum concurrent runs. Defaults to the value in `.cloche/config.toml`. |\n\n`cloche loop stop` disables the loop. Running tasks are not cancelled.\n\n### `cloche shutdown`\n\n```\ncloche shutdown\n```\n\n## Project Layout\n\n```\nmy-project/\n‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ .cloche/\n‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ develop.cloche        # Container workflow\n‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ host.cloche           # Host orchestration workflow\n‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ Dockerfile            # Container image definition\n‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ config.toml           # Project configuration\n‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ prompts/              # Prompt templates\n‚îÇ   ‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ implement.md\n‚îÇ   ‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ fix.md\n‚îÇ   ‚îÇ   ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ update-docs.md\n‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ scripts/              # Host-side scripts\n‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ overrides/            # Files copied on top of /workspace/\n‚îÇ   ‚îÇ   ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ CLAUDE.md         # Container-specific CLAUDE.md (optional)\n‚îÇ   ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ <run-id>/             # Runtime state (gitignored)\n‚îÇ       ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ prompt.txt        # User prompt\n‚îÇ       ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ context.json      # Shared key-value store (cloche get/set)\n‚îÇ       ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ output/\n‚îÇ       ‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ full.log      # Unified log\n‚îÇ       ‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ test.log      # Per-step script output\n‚îÇ       ‚îÇ   ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ llm-impl.log  # Per-step LLM conversation\n‚îÇ       ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ attempt_count/    # Retry counters for max_attempts\n‚îÇ       ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ history.log       # Step execution log\n‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ src/                      # Project source (untouched by Cloche)\n‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ .git/\n```\n\n## Daemon Configuration\n\n| Variable | Default | Description |\n|----------|---------|-------------|\n| `CLOCHE_LISTEN` | `unix:///tmp/cloche.sock` | Listen address |\n| `CLOCHE_DB` | `cloche.db` | SQLite database path |\n| `CLOCHE_RUNTIME` | `docker` | `docker` or `local` (subprocess, for dev only) |\n| `CLOCHE_IMAGE` | `cloche-agent:latest` | Default Docker image |\n| `CLOCHE_HTTP` | _(unset)_ | HTTP address for web dashboard. Not started unless set. |\n| `CLOCHE_AGENT_PATH` | _(auto)_ | Path to `cloche-agent` binary (local runtime) |\n| `CLOCHE_LLM_COMMAND` | _(unset)_ | Command for LLM calls (evolution, merge conflicts) |\n| `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` | _(unset)_ | Passed into Docker containers |\n| `CLOCHE_EXTRA_MOUNTS` | _(unset)_ | Extra bind mounts (comma-separated `host:container`) |\n| `CLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV` | _(unset)_ | Extra env vars (comma-separated `KEY=VALUE`) |\n\n### Client Configuration\n\n| Variable | Default | Description |\n|----------|---------|-------------|\n| `CLOCHE_ADDR` | `unix:///tmp/cloche.sock` | Daemon gRPC address |\n| `CLOCHE_HTTP` | `localhost:8080` | Daemon HTTP address |\n\n## Dockerfile Requirements\n\nThe container image must have:\n- `cloche-agent` binary at `/usr/local/bin/cloche-agent`\n- `git` installed\n- An `agent` user (cloche wraps commands with `chown` + `su agent`)\n- `/workspace` as the working directory\n- Your project's build dependencies and the agent binary (e.g. `claude`)\n\n## Build Commands\n\n```\nmake build          # Build all binaries to bin/\nmake test           # Run all tests\nmake test-short     # Run tests (skip slow ones)\nmake lint           # Run go vet\nmake proto          # Regenerate gRPC code from protobuf\nmake docker-build   # Build the cloche-agent Docker image\nmake install        # Build, install to ~/.local/bin/, restart daemon\nmake clean          # Remove bin/\n```\n","numLines":664,"startLine":1,"totalLines":664}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01TqSNrnNPq4x1KB81X59st4","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_011sqw4C9PpA853ucpG3b61r","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/workspace/docs/workflows.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1181,"cache_read_input_tokens":42755,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1181},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2090add2-0fe6-4270-9f3b-b52deb6bac91","uuid":"f4af436a-1cc8-4b97-be6f-092b37370682"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_011sqw4C9PpA853ucpG3b61r","type":"tool_result","content":"     1‚Üí# Workflows\n     2‚Üí\n     3‚ÜíCloche workflows define a directed graph of steps connected by named results.\n     4‚Üí\n     5‚Üí## Workflow Locations\n     6‚Üí\n     7‚ÜíCloche distinguishes two workflow locations based on the file they live in:\n     8‚Üí\n     9‚Üí**Container workflows** (`.cloche/*.cloche` except `host.cloche`) ‚Äî Run inside a Docker\n    10‚Üícontainer via `cloche-agent`. Steps may only be `agent` or `script` type. These are the\n    11‚Üístandard workflows for coding tasks.\n    12‚Üí\n    13‚Üí**Host workflows** (`.cloche/host.cloche`) ‚Äî Run on the host machine as the daemon\n    14‚Üíprocess. Steps may be `agent`, `script`, or `workflow` type. The `workflow` step type\n    15‚Üídispatches a container workflow run and waits for it to complete. This is the extension\n    16‚Üípoint for custom orchestration strategies.\n    17‚Üí\n    18‚ÜíA single `host.cloche` file may contain **multiple named workflows**. The daemon\n    19‚Üíuses up to three workflow phases for orchestration:\n    20‚Üí\n    21‚Üí| Phase | Workflow name | Purpose |\n    22‚Üí|-------|--------------|---------|\n    23‚Üí| 1 | `list-tasks` | Discover available work. Output is JSONL (one task per line). |\n    24‚Üí| 2 | `main` | Do the work. Receives a task ID via `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` env var. |\n    25‚Üí| 3 | `finalize` | Post-main cleanup. Runs on **both** success and failure. |\n    26‚Üí\n    27‚ÜíOnly `main` is required. If `list-tasks` is absent, the daemon uses a legacy\n    28‚Üísingle-function mode. If `finalize` is absent, it is skipped.\n    29‚Üí\n    30‚ÜíThe `list-tasks` workflow's final step output is parsed as JSONL. Each line is a JSON\n    31‚Üíobject with the following fields:\n    32‚Üí\n    33‚Üí| Field | Required | Description |\n    34‚Üí|-------|----------|-------------|\n    35‚Üí| `id` | yes | Unique task identifier |\n    36‚Üí| `status` | yes | One of `open`, `closed`, `in-progress` |\n    37‚Üí| `title` | no | Short summary |\n    38‚Üí| `description` | no | Full description |\n    39‚Üí| `metadata` | no | Arbitrary key-value pairs |\n    40‚Üí\n    41‚ÜíThe daemon picks the first task with status `open` (or empty, for backward\n    42‚Üícompatibility), runs `main` with that task ID, then runs `finalize` with the outcome.\n    43‚ÜíTasks are deduplicated within a configurable timeout window to prevent rapid\n    44‚Üíreassignment.\n    45‚Üí\n    46‚ÜíThe convention is enforced at parse time: a `workflow_name` step in a container workflow\n    47‚Üífile is a parse error.\n    48‚Üí\n    49‚Üí## Concepts\n    50‚Üí\n    51‚Üí| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n    52‚Üí|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n    53‚Üí| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n    54‚Üí| step     | A unit of work (inferred: `prompt` = agent, `run` = script)        |\n    55‚Üí| result   | A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. \"success\", \"fail\")       |\n    56‚Üí| wiring   | Maps a step's result to the next step, with optional output mappings |\n    57‚Üí| done     | Built-in terminal step ‚Äî successful completion                     |\n    58‚Üí| abort    | Built-in terminal step ‚Äî failure with error reporting              |\n    59‚Üí\n    60‚Üí## Step Types\n    61‚Üí\n    62‚ÜíStep type is inferred from the fields present in the step body:\n    63‚Üí\n    64‚Üí**agent** (has `prompt`) ‚Äî Invokes a coding agent (Claude Code, or any tool conforming\n    65‚Üíto the agent adapter interface) with a prompt. The agent works autonomously inside the\n    66‚Üícontainer. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    67‚Üí\n    68‚Üí**script** (has `run`) ‚Äî Runs a shell command. Used for tests, linters, validators, or\n    69‚Üíany deterministic check. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    70‚Üí\n    71‚Üí**workflow** (has `workflow_name`) ‚Äî Dispatches a named container workflow run and blocks\n    72‚Üíuntil it completes. Only available in host workflows (`host.cloche`).\n    73‚Üí\n    74‚ÜíA step with more than one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`, or none of them, is a\n    75‚Üíparse error.\n    76‚Üí\n    77‚Üí## DSL Syntax\n    78‚Üí\n    79‚Üí```\n    80‚Üíworkflow \"develop\" {\n    81‚Üí  container {\n    82‚Üí    image = \"my-project:latest\"\n    83‚Üí    agent_command = \"claude\"\n    84‚Üí  }\n    85‚Üí\n    86‚Üí  step implement {\n    87‚Üí    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    88‚Üí    results = [success, fail]\n    89‚Üí  }\n    90‚Üí\n    91‚Üí  step test {\n    92‚Üí    run = \"make test && make lint\"\n    93‚Üí    results = [success, fail]\n    94‚Üí  }\n    95‚Üí\n    96‚Üí  step fix {\n    97‚Üí    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/fix.md\")\n    98‚Üí    max_attempts = \"3\"\n    99‚Üí    results = [success, fail, give-up]\n   100‚Üí  }\n   101‚Üí\n   102‚Üí  // Wiring: step:result -> next_step [optional output mappings]\n   103‚Üí  implement:success -> test\n   104‚Üí  implement:fail    -> abort\n   105‚Üí  test:success      -> done\n   106‚Üí  test:fail         -> fix\n   107‚Üí  fix:success       -> test\n   108‚Üí  fix:fail          -> abort\n   109‚Üí  fix:give-up       -> abort\n   110‚Üí}\n   111‚Üí```\n   112‚Üí\n   113‚Üí## Key Properties\n   114‚Üí\n   115‚Üí**Step type is inferred from content.** A `prompt` field makes it an agent step; a `run`\n   116‚Üífield makes it a script step.\n   117‚Üí\n   118‚Üí**Steps declare their possible results.** A step decides at runtime which result to\n   119‚Üíreport. The graph engine follows the wiring to determine the next step.\n   120‚Üí\n   121‚Üí**Wiring is separate from step definitions.** This enables inserting new steps between\n   122‚Üíexisting ones by rewiring ‚Äî without modifying either step. This is the foundation for\n   123‚ÜíCloche's self-evolution feature.\n   124‚Üí\n   125‚Üí**Graphs are validated at parse time.** The parser checks that all declared results are\n   126‚Üíwired, no steps are orphaned, and an entry point exists.\n   127‚Üí\n   128‚Üí## Wire Output Mappings\n   129‚Üí\n   130‚ÜíWires can include output mappings that extract values from a step's output and inject\n   131‚Üíthem as environment variables into the target step:\n   132‚Üí\n   133‚Üí```\n   134‚Üístep-a:success -> step-b [ ENV_VAR = output.field, OTHER = output.list[0].name ]\n   135‚Üí```\n   136‚Üí\n   137‚ÜíThe general form:\n   138‚Üí\n   139‚Üí```\n   140‚ÜíFROM:RESULT -> TO [ KEY = EXPR, KEY = EXPR, ... ]\n   141‚Üí```\n   142‚Üí\n   143‚ÜíWhere `KEY` is the environment variable name and `EXPR` is an output path expression\n   144‚Üístarting with the contextual keyword `output`:\n   145‚Üí\n   146‚Üí| Expression | Meaning |\n   147‚Üí|---|---|\n   148‚Üí| `output` | Raw output (full string) |\n   149‚Üí| `output.key` | JSON object field access |\n   150‚Üí| `output[N]` | JSON array index (0-based) |\n   151‚Üí| `output.a.b.c` | Deeply nested field access |\n   152‚Üí| `output.items[0].name` | Mixed field and index chaining |\n   153‚Üí\n   154‚ÜíIf the source step's output is valid JSON, path expressions navigate the parsed\n   155‚Üístructure. If the output is plain text, only bare `output` is valid. The resolved\n   156‚Üívalue is converted to a string for env var injection.\n   157‚Üí\n   158‚ÜíIf two wires targeting the same step both map the same env var key, validation\n   159‚Üíreturns an error (the mapping would be ambiguous). The same key may be used on\n   160‚Üíwires to different steps without conflict.\n   161‚Üí\n   162‚Üí## Workflow-Level Configuration Blocks\n   163‚Üí\n   164‚ÜíWorkflows support a configuration block at the workflow level to set defaults for all\n   165‚Üísteps. The block name depends on the workflow location:\n   166‚Üí\n   167‚Üí**`container {}`** ‚Äî For container workflows. Sets container image, agent command, and\n   168‚Üínetwork allowlist.\n   169‚Üí\n   170‚Üí```\n   171‚Üíworkflow \"develop\" {\n   172‚Üí  container {\n   173‚Üí    image = \"my-project:latest\"\n   174‚Üí    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   175‚Üí    agent_args = \"-p --dangerously-skip-permissions\"\n   176‚Üí  }\n   177‚Üí  ...\n   178‚Üí}\n   179‚Üí```\n   180‚Üí\n   181‚ÜíSupported keys: `image`, `agent_command`, `agent_args`, `network_allow`.\n   182‚Üí\n   183‚Üí**`host {}`** ‚Äî For host workflows (`host.cloche`). Sets agent defaults for agent steps\n   184‚Üírunning on the host machine.\n   185‚Üí\n   186‚Üí```\n   187‚Üíworkflow \"main\" {\n   188‚Üí  host {\n   189‚Üí    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   190‚Üí  }\n   191‚Üí  ...\n   192‚Üí}\n   193‚Üí```\n   194‚Üí\n   195‚ÜíSupported keys: `agent_command`, `agent_args`.\n   196‚Üí\n   197‚ÜíStep-level `agent_command` and `agent_args` override workflow-level defaults. The\n   198‚Üíresolution order is: step-level > workflow-level block > `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` env\n   199‚Üívar > default `claude`.\n   200‚Üí\n   201‚Üí## Host Workflow Example\n   202‚Üí\n   203‚ÜíA three-phase `host.cloche` with separate `list-tasks`, `main`, and `finalize`\n   204‚Üíworkflows:\n   205‚Üí\n   206‚Üí```\n   207‚Üí# .cloche/host.cloche ‚Äî runs on the host machine\n   208‚Üí\n   209‚Üíworkflow \"list-tasks\" {\n   210‚Üí  step fetch-tickets {\n   211‚Üí    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n   212‚Üí    results = [success, fail]\n   213‚Üí  }\n   214‚Üí\n   215‚Üí  fetch-tickets:success -> done\n   216‚Üí  fetch-tickets:fail    -> abort\n   217‚Üí}\n   218‚Üí\n   219‚Üíworkflow \"main\" {\n   220‚Üí  host {\n   221‚Üí    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   222‚Üí  }\n   223‚Üí\n   224‚Üí  step prepare-prompt {\n   225‚Üí    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n   226‚Üí    results = [success, fail]\n   227‚Üí  }\n   228‚Üí\n   229‚Üí  step develop {\n   230‚Üí    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n   231‚Üí    results       = [success, fail]\n   232‚Üí  }\n   233‚Üí\n   234‚Üí  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n   235‚Üí  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n   236‚Üí  develop:success        -> done\n   237‚Üí  develop:fail           -> done\n   238‚Üí}\n   239‚Üí\n   240‚Üíworkflow \"finalize\" {\n   241‚Üí  step push-for-review {\n   242‚Üí    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/push-for-review.sh\"\n   243‚Üí    results = [success, fail]\n   244‚Üí  }\n   245‚Üí\n   246‚Üí  push-for-review:success -> done\n   247‚Üí  push-for-review:fail    -> done\n   248‚Üí}\n   249‚Üí```\n   250‚Üí\n   251‚ÜíThe daemon runs `list-tasks` to discover work (output is JSONL), picks an open task,\n   252‚Üíruns `main` with `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` set, then runs `finalize` regardless of outcome.\n   253‚ÜíThe `list-tasks` script writes one JSON object per line to `$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`.\n   254‚ÜíThe `main` workflow receives the task ID and is responsible for claiming the ticket.\n   255‚ÜíThe `finalize` workflow decides what to do based on the outcome (available via\n   256‚Üí`CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` env vars).\n   257‚Üí\n   258‚Üí## Execution Model\n   259‚Üí\n   260‚Üí**Container workflows** are parsed and executed by `cloche-agent` inside a Docker\n   261‚Üícontainer. The agent walks the graph: execute current step, read its result, follow the\n   262‚Üíwiring to the next step. This continues until a terminal (`done` or `abort`) is reached.\n   263‚ÜíAll steps run inside the same container. File state accumulates naturally across steps.\n   264‚Üí\n   265‚Üí**Host workflows** are parsed and executed by the daemon on the host machine. A single\n   266‚Üí`host.cloche` file may contain multiple named workflows; the daemon orchestrates them\n   267‚Üíin three phases (list-tasks ‚Üí main ‚Üí finalize). Script steps run via `sh -c` with the\n   268‚Üíworking directory set to the **main git worktree** (i.e. the main branch checkout), even\n   269‚Üíif the project directory is a linked worktree on a different branch. This ensures\n   270‚Üíhost-workflow scripts from main are used for all runs. Workflow steps dispatch container\n   271‚Üíruns via the daemon's standard run pipeline. Environment variables (`CLOCHE_TASK_ID`,\n   272‚Üí`CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR`, etc.) are injected into each step; `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` still\n   273‚Üípoints to the actual project directory.\n   274‚Üí"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2090add2-0fe6-4270-9f3b-b52deb6bac91","uuid":"9f335a1c-656f-475c-a5c2-cfc64535e5d8","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/docs/workflows.md","content":"# Workflows\n\nCloche workflows define a directed graph of steps connected by named results.\n\n## Workflow Locations\n\nCloche distinguishes two workflow locations based on the file they live in:\n\n**Container workflows** (`.cloche/*.cloche` except `host.cloche`) ‚Äî Run inside a Docker\ncontainer via `cloche-agent`. Steps may only be `agent` or `script` type. These are the\nstandard workflows for coding tasks.\n\n**Host workflows** (`.cloche/host.cloche`) ‚Äî Run on the host machine as the daemon\nprocess. Steps may be `agent`, `script`, or `workflow` type. The `workflow` step type\ndispatches a container workflow run and waits for it to complete. This is the extension\npoint for custom orchestration strategies.\n\nA single `host.cloche` file may contain **multiple named workflows**. The daemon\nuses up to three workflow phases for orchestration:\n\n| Phase | Workflow name | Purpose |\n|-------|--------------|---------|\n| 1 | `list-tasks` | Discover available work. Output is JSONL (one task per line). |\n| 2 | `main` | Do the work. Receives a task ID via `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` env var. |\n| 3 | `finalize` | Post-main cleanup. Runs on **both** success and failure. |\n\nOnly `main` is required. If `list-tasks` is absent, the daemon uses a legacy\nsingle-function mode. If `finalize` is absent, it is skipped.\n\nThe `list-tasks` workflow's final step output is parsed as JSONL. Each line is a JSON\nobject with the following fields:\n\n| Field | Required | Description |\n|-------|----------|-------------|\n| `id` | yes | Unique task identifier |\n| `status` | yes | One of `open`, `closed`, `in-progress` |\n| `title` | no | Short summary |\n| `description` | no | Full description |\n| `metadata` | no | Arbitrary key-value pairs |\n\nThe daemon picks the first task with status `open` (or empty, for backward\ncompatibility), runs `main` with that task ID, then runs `finalize` with the outcome.\nTasks are deduplicated within a configurable timeout window to prevent rapid\nreassignment.\n\nThe convention is enforced at parse time: a `workflow_name` step in a container workflow\nfile is a parse error.\n\n## Concepts\n\n| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n| step     | A unit of work (inferred: `prompt` = agent, `run` = script)        |\n| result   | A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. \"success\", \"fail\")       |\n| wiring   | Maps a step's result to the next step, with optional output mappings |\n| done     | Built-in terminal step ‚Äî successful completion                     |\n| abort    | Built-in terminal step ‚Äî failure with error reporting              |\n\n## Step Types\n\nStep type is inferred from the fields present in the step body:\n\n**agent** (has `prompt`) ‚Äî Invokes a coding agent (Claude Code, or any tool conforming\nto the agent adapter interface) with a prompt. The agent works autonomously inside the\ncontainer. Available in both host and container workflows.\n\n**script** (has `run`) ‚Äî Runs a shell command. Used for tests, linters, validators, or\nany deterministic check. Available in both host and container workflows.\n\n**workflow** (has `workflow_name`) ‚Äî Dispatches a named container workflow run and blocks\nuntil it completes. Only available in host workflows (`host.cloche`).\n\nA step with more than one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`, or none of them, is a\nparse error.\n\n## DSL Syntax\n\n```\nworkflow \"develop\" {\n  container {\n    image = \"my-project:latest\"\n    agent_command = \"claude\"\n  }\n\n  step implement {\n    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step test {\n    run = \"make test && make lint\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step fix {\n    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/fix.md\")\n    max_attempts = \"3\"\n    results = [success, fail, give-up]\n  }\n\n  // Wiring: step:result -> next_step [optional output mappings]\n  implement:success -> test\n  implement:fail    -> abort\n  test:success      -> done\n  test:fail         -> fix\n  fix:success       -> test\n  fix:fail          -> abort\n  fix:give-up       -> abort\n}\n```\n\n## Key Properties\n\n**Step type is inferred from content.** A `prompt` field makes it an agent step; a `run`\nfield makes it a script step.\n\n**Steps declare their possible results.** A step decides at runtime which result to\nreport. The graph engine follows the wiring to determine the next step.\n\n**Wiring is separate from step definitions.** This enables inserting new steps between\nexisting ones by rewiring ‚Äî without modifying either step. This is the foundation for\nCloche's self-evolution feature.\n\n**Graphs are validated at parse time.** The parser checks that all declared results are\nwired, no steps are orphaned, and an entry point exists.\n\n## Wire Output Mappings\n\nWires can include output mappings that extract values from a step's output and inject\nthem as environment variables into the target step:\n\n```\nstep-a:success -> step-b [ ENV_VAR = output.field, OTHER = output.list[0].name ]\n```\n\nThe general form:\n\n```\nFROM:RESULT -> TO [ KEY = EXPR, KEY = EXPR, ... ]\n```\n\nWhere `KEY` is the environment variable name and `EXPR` is an output path expression\nstarting with the contextual keyword `output`:\n\n| Expression | Meaning |\n|---|---|\n| `output` | Raw output (full string) |\n| `output.key` | JSON object field access |\n| `output[N]` | JSON array index (0-based) |\n| `output.a.b.c` | Deeply nested field access |\n| `output.items[0].name` | Mixed field and index chaining |\n\nIf the source step's output is valid JSON, path expressions navigate the parsed\nstructure. If the output is plain text, only bare `output` is valid. The resolved\nvalue is converted to a string for env var injection.\n\nIf two wires targeting the same step both map the same env var key, validation\nreturns an error (the mapping would be ambiguous). The same key may be used on\nwires to different steps without conflict.\n\n## Workflow-Level Configuration Blocks\n\nWorkflows support a configuration block at the workflow level to set defaults for all\nsteps. The block name depends on the workflow location:\n\n**`container {}`** ‚Äî For container workflows. Sets container image, agent command, and\nnetwork allowlist.\n\n```\nworkflow \"develop\" {\n  container {\n    image = \"my-project:latest\"\n    agent_command = \"claude\"\n    agent_args = \"-p --dangerously-skip-permissions\"\n  }\n  ...\n}\n```\n\nSupported keys: `image`, `agent_command`, `agent_args`, `network_allow`.\n\n**`host {}`** ‚Äî For host workflows (`host.cloche`). Sets agent defaults for agent steps\nrunning on the host machine.\n\n```\nworkflow \"main\" {\n  host {\n    agent_command = \"claude\"\n  }\n  ...\n}\n```\n\nSupported keys: `agent_command`, `agent_args`.\n\nStep-level `agent_command` and `agent_args` override workflow-level defaults. The\nresolution order is: step-level > workflow-level block > `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` env\nvar > default `claude`.\n\n## Host Workflow Example\n\nA three-phase `host.cloche` with separate `list-tasks`, `main`, and `finalize`\nworkflows:\n\n```\n# .cloche/host.cloche ‚Äî runs on the host machine\n\nworkflow \"list-tasks\" {\n  step fetch-tickets {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  fetch-tickets:success -> done\n  fetch-tickets:fail    -> abort\n}\n\nworkflow \"main\" {\n  host {\n    agent_command = \"claude\"\n  }\n\n  step prepare-prompt {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step develop {\n    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n    results       = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n  develop:success        -> done\n  develop:fail           -> done\n}\n\nworkflow \"finalize\" {\n  step push-for-review {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/push-for-review.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  push-for-review:success -> done\n  push-for-review:fail    -> done\n}\n```\n\nThe daemon runs `list-tasks` to discover work (output is JSONL), picks an open task,\nruns `main` with `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` set, then runs `finalize` regardless of outcome.\nThe `list-tasks` script writes one JSON object per line to `$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`.\nThe `main` workflow receives the task ID and is responsible for claiming the ticket.\nThe `finalize` workflow decides what to do based on the outcome (available via\n`CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` env vars).\n\n## Execution Model\n\n**Container workflows** are parsed and executed by `cloche-agent` inside a Docker\ncontainer. The agent walks the graph: execute current step, read its result, follow the\nwiring to the next step. This continues until a terminal (`done` or `abort`) is reached.\nAll steps run inside the same container. File state accumulates naturally across steps.\n\n**Host workflows** are parsed and executed by the daemon on the host machine. A single\n`host.cloche` file may contain multiple named workflows; the daemon orchestrates them\nin three phases (list-tasks ‚Üí main ‚Üí finalize). Script steps run via `sh -c` with the\nworking directory set to the **main git worktree** (i.e. the main branch checkout), even\nif the project directory is a linked worktree on a different branch. This ensures\nhost-workflow scripts from main are used for all runs. Workflow steps dispatch container\nruns via the daemon's standard run pipeline. Environment variables (`CLOCHE_TASK_ID`,\n`CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR`, etc.) are injected into each step; `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` still\npoints to the actual project directory.\n","numLines":274,"startLine":1,"totalLines":274}}}
